WEBVTT

00:02.003 --> 00:06.087
[Chattering ]
[ Hammering ]

00:12.597 --> 00:15.714
I want all the venting
double—checked for leaks.

00:15.808 --> 00:19.517
And put plastic guards
on any sharp corners of tables or gurneys.

00:19.645 --> 00:21.727
Do we have enough suits
for everyone?
Just.

00:21.814 --> 00:23.600
These last two are for us.

00:23.691 --> 00:27.104
The rep from the CDC. is downstairs in
Holding, waiting until we’re set up.

00:27.195 --> 00:31.234
The CDC. sent over
preliminary photos from the body find.

00:31.324 --> 00:35.613
They were inspecting a facility in Maryland
that disposes of biohazard waste.

00:35.745 --> 00:38.657
And the remains were found
with veterinary waste?
Yeah.

00:38.748 --> 00:42.036
I’m gonna have a hell of a time
with a skull that damaged.

00:42.126 --> 00:44.117
Do they have any idea what the infection is?

00:44.212 --> 00:46.373
They initially suspected
necrotizing fasciitis.

00:46.505 --> 00:47.915
Flesh—eating disease?
Yes.

00:48.007 --> 00:49.918
[ Brennan ]
But the decomposition was too rapid,

00:50.009 --> 00:52.000
and it wouldn’t have damaged
the bone so severely.

00:52.094 --> 00:55.382
Damage that advanced from fasciitis would
normally take at least three to four days.

00:55.473 --> 00:57.885
Dr. Jacobs from the C.D.C.
has taken initial cultures,

00:57.975 --> 01:01.058
but so far they don’t know
if it’s viral or bacterial...

01:01.145 --> 01:03.181
or airborne or blood—borne.

01:03.272 --> 01:06.105
So we could be looking
at some kind of outbreak situation here?

01:06.192 --> 01:08.148
We have to assume so, yes.

01:12.073 --> 01:14.405
I thought biohazard facilities
had strict protocols.

01:14.492 --> 01:16.357
How can someone just
dump a body in there?

01:16.452 --> 01:19.068
The place has been cited twice before
for security breaches.

01:19.163 --> 01:21.529
That’s why the C.D.C. showed up
for a surprise inspection.

01:21.666 --> 01:24.123
Any word from
the Jeffersonian yet?
Nope, not yet. Not a word.

01:24.210 --> 01:27.247
They’re putting on their space suits
before they even look at the victim.

01:27.338 --> 01:30.455
I’m telling you, usually I hope a killer is
sloppy— makes them easier to catch.

01:30.549 --> 01:33.256
Yeah, except this time
being sloppy could cause a pandemic.

01:33.344 --> 01:34.800
[ Exhales ]

01:34.887 --> 01:36.673
- [ Hodg/ns / / have a mass spec up there?
— [ Saroyan ] Yes.

01:36.806 --> 01:39.047
And a centrifuge?
Yes, Dr. Hodgins.
It’s all up there.

01:39.141 --> 01:41.268
Angela, all your camera equipment
and scanning equipment’s...

01:41.352 --> 01:42.888
been set up next to the light table.

01:42.979 --> 01:45.436
And the direct Ethernet link
to the servers in my office?

01:45.523 --> 01:47.354
— They’re finishing cabling now.
- Okay.

01:48.818 --> 01:51.981
— Dr. Saroyan?
— Uh, l’m Dr. Saroyan.

01:52.071 --> 01:56.235
— And this is Dr. Brennan.
— lvan Jacobs. It is an honor
to be working with you all here.

01:56.325 --> 02:00.443
Dr. Jacobs, you were on the front line
in Turkey during the H5N1 outbreak.

02:00.538 --> 02:03.530
Yes. And I’ve spent the past six months
with the W.H.O. in the Congo,

02:03.624 --> 02:05.330
and l have not seen
anything like this before.

02:05.459 --> 02:07.836
You took preliminary
viral cultures?
Yes.

02:07.920 --> 02:09.535
lt’s virulent and replicating quickly.

02:09.630 --> 02:12.167
But we need additional cultures
and more analysis to give us a strain.

02:12.258 --> 02:14.249
We were hoping that an ID. of the victim...

02:14.343 --> 02:16.254
could provide where she
contracted the infection.

02:16.387 --> 02:19.345
Then let’s get working.
l’ll suit up.

02:21.851 --> 02:23.341
[ Beeping ]

02:31.402 --> 02:32.892
Was this person tortured?

02:32.987 --> 02:35.069
We think the nervous system was hit,

02:35.156 --> 02:36.612
which caused the muscles to seize.

02:36.699 --> 02:40.317
Based on the occipital and pelvic outlet,
the decedent’s a female.

02:40.411 --> 02:44.871
The wear on the mandibular teeth indicates
an age between 25 and 35 years old.

02:44.957 --> 02:48.415
There are lesions on
the long bones and the ribs.

02:48.502 --> 02:50.208
They seem to have developed recently.

02:50.296 --> 02:53.379
— Had to be within the past 24 hours.
— She’s turning into soup.

02:53.466 --> 02:56.003
We’re dealing with
a single—stranded RNA. virus,

02:56.093 --> 02:58.800
a mutation that doesn’t depend
on the cell cycle to replicate.

02:58.888 --> 03:02.506
- Which accounts for its speed.
- And why we’re seeing such
severe damage to the bones.

03:02.600 --> 03:07.845
The blood remaining in the heart wouldn’t be
as contaminated by decompositional tissue.

03:07.938 --> 03:11.305
I’ll use leukocyte depletion filters
to single out white blood cells,

03:11.400 --> 03:12.981
see what kind of infection
we’re dealing with here.

03:13.069 --> 03:14.855
There’s insect larvae on her clothes.

03:14.945 --> 03:17.072
This could tell us where she was
before she was dumped.

03:17.156 --> 03:19.522
I hope so. We need to ID. the victim
as quickly as possible.

03:19.617 --> 03:22.609
If we know who she is,
we might understand what did this to her.

03:27.166 --> 03:28.952
[Camera Shutter Clicks]

04:02.493 --> 04:05.109
[Ringing]

04:10.042 --> 04:12.954
Hi, Booth.
This is Dr. Jacobs from the C.D.C.

04:13.045 --> 04:17.004
Hey. Okay, listen, the biohazard facility
can’t tell us where the body came from.

04:17.133 --> 04:20.671
The records, they’re a mess.
And everything that was supposed
to be burned got mixed together.

04:20.761 --> 04:22.717
That’s common when the remains
have been mislabeled.

04:22.805 --> 04:26.593
She was placed in a level—one containment
bag along with veterinary waste.

04:26.684 --> 04:28.140
Do you have an ID. yet?

04:28.227 --> 04:30.843
Well, whoever did this didn’t want us to.

04:30.938 --> 04:33.725
- Oh, my God.
— [ Jacobs ] What? You can’t get an ID?

04:33.816 --> 04:35.807
There’s not enough tissue left
for fingerprints.

04:35.901 --> 04:38.108
This bone damage isn’t from the disease.

04:38.195 --> 04:42.609
Someone smashed the teeth, mandible
and maxilla to prevent a dental l.D.

04:42.700 --> 04:46.067
l’m scanning to at least get
a close facial approximation.

04:46.162 --> 04:49.074
Whoever did this knows how dangerous
this virus is and was trying to hide it.

04:49.165 --> 04:50.871
Well, but why?

04:50.958 --> 04:52.789
Maybe they intend to infect other people...

04:52.877 --> 04:55.493
and they don’t want anyone
knowing how to stop them.

04:55.588 --> 04:57.829
Bones, we’re talking about
bioterrorism here.

05:00.092 --> 05:01.593
I know.

05:48.641 --> 05:50.131
Are you any closer?

05:50.226 --> 05:51.841
Since I only have a partial
reconstruction,

05:51.936 --> 05:53.597
I’m getting multiple hits.

05:53.687 --> 05:56.474
Hodgins found evidence that
she was last in Coral Hills, Maryland,

05:56.565 --> 05:58.806
before she wound up
in the biohazard facility.

05:58.901 --> 06:02.439
Okay, well, all these D.M.V. hits are from
Maryland, so I must be getting close.

06:02.530 --> 06:06.148
Those three don’t match. Their temporal
bones aren’t angled like the victim’s.

06:06.242 --> 06:07.698
The recognition program—

06:07.785 --> 06:09.275
That woman seems like a closer match,

06:09.370 --> 06:11.452
but the victim’s zygomatic
is more pronounced.

06:12.998 --> 06:14.534
That’s her. That’s her.

06:14.625 --> 06:16.957
Okay.

06:20.506 --> 06:21.621
[ Exhales ]

06:22.341 --> 06:23.922
Wow.

06:24.009 --> 06:25.545
Mia Garrett.

06:25.636 --> 06:28.969
So why do we pay eight zillion dollars
for the software when we have you?

06:29.056 --> 06:32.264
Under normal circumstances,
it allows me to take a longer lunch.

06:32.351 --> 06:33.841
I’ll tell Booth.

06:33.936 --> 06:35.722
[Man /
Are you sure it was Mia?

06:35.813 --> 06:39.522
Yeah. I’m very sorry
for your loss, Mr. Carr.

06:39.608 --> 06:42.566
We were talking about getting married,
picking out different places for the ceremony.

06:42.653 --> 06:45.235
You had no idea where she’d
been for the past three days?

06:45.322 --> 06:48.439
No. l was traveling.
She wasn’t answering her phone.

06:48.534 --> 06:50.741
That didn’t worry you—
not knowing where she was?

06:50.828 --> 06:52.534
It wasn’t unusual.

06:52.621 --> 06:54.862
She was working on a story,
and she needed space.

06:54.957 --> 06:56.572
I didn’t have a problem with that.

06:56.667 --> 07:00.205
— She’s a journalist?
- Yeah. A blogger. Me too.

07:00.296 --> 07:03.459
We both were trying for that story
that would make the headlines.

07:03.549 --> 07:05.915
Did she write about terrorism,
by any chance?

07:06.010 --> 07:07.375
Terrorism? No.

07:07.469 --> 07:09.334
Her focus was on Big Pharma,

07:09.430 --> 07:11.762
medical research, doping,
that kind of stuff.

07:11.890 --> 07:14.267
What do you write about, Ben?
Travel.

07:14.351 --> 07:15.761
Nothing too exciting.

07:15.853 --> 07:18.970
Look, l-l told Mia what she
was working on was dangerous.

07:19.064 --> 07:21.555
Those people she was investigating
have money, power.

07:21.650 --> 07:23.641
They don’t want some blogger poking around.

07:23.736 --> 07:26.569
What was the last thing she was working on?

07:26.655 --> 07:28.395
| wish I knew.

07:28.490 --> 07:30.446
She said it could’ve been the one.

07:30.534 --> 07:33.776
But Mia liked to keep things
to herself until she finished the project.

07:33.871 --> 07:35.361
Didn’t she trust you?

07:35.456 --> 07:37.663
Well, of course she trusted me.

07:37.750 --> 07:40.583
| just told you we were thinking
about getting married.

07:40.669 --> 07:44.161
Just th—that story,
she didn’t want to tell me. For now.

07:44.256 --> 07:46.713
Sounds like she didn’t trust you.

07:51.180 --> 07:53.421
The bone damage is reminiscent
of multiple myeloma.

07:53.515 --> 07:55.426
But there’s no cancer that moves this fast.

07:55.559 --> 07:59.268
There are some viral strains of
the psittacosis—lymphogranuloma
venereum group...

07:59.355 --> 08:01.141
that have been known to affect bone.

08:01.231 --> 08:02.607
[Computer Beeping ]

08:02.691 --> 08:05.182
It’s the preliminary pathology
from the blood work.

08:11.784 --> 08:13.615
There are no aerosolized pathogens.

08:13.702 --> 08:15.363
— Thank God.
— It’s not airborne?

08:15.454 --> 08:16.990
It’s not airborne.

08:17.081 --> 08:20.573
So it had to come through a transfer
of blood or fluid or an injection.

08:20.668 --> 08:22.875
So we can eliminate bioterrorism?

08:22.961 --> 08:25.953
Well, not completely,
but it would seem a stretch.

08:26.048 --> 08:28.460
One thing’s for sure—
we’re not gonna need this tent anymore.

08:28.550 --> 08:30.336
I think that deserves another “thank God.”

08:30.427 --> 08:32.133
[ Cell Phone Ringing /

08:32.221 --> 08:34.553
Booth. Okay.

08:34.640 --> 08:37.006
You sure? Yeah. That’s great news, Bones.

08:37.101 --> 08:39.467
Okay. Great. Yeah. You too.

08:39.561 --> 08:42.303
All right, good news.
The, uh— The virus isn’t airborne.

08:42.439 --> 08:44.100
They’re safe.
That’s a load off.

08:44.191 --> 08:47.149
That is. I can’t even think about Bones
being in there with all those germs.

08:47.236 --> 08:48.942
Give me a guy with a gun anytime.

08:49.029 --> 08:50.735
Now we have to find out
what Mia was working on.

08:50.823 --> 08:53.781
Angela’s looking at her laptop now.

08:55.160 --> 08:56.821
Mia encrypted everything.

08:56.912 --> 09:02.032
Her e—mails, documents all used
a steganographic encryption.

09:02.126 --> 09:04.492
She was wicked smart.

09:04.586 --> 09:06.326
What just happened?

09:06.422 --> 09:09.129
That is me being smarter than her.

09:09.216 --> 09:13.334
Okay, ljust intercepted
an e—mail, probably spam.

09:13.429 --> 09:16.011
It shows me how
the encryption process works.

09:16.098 --> 09:19.716
Because it has to create
an opening to accept the e—mail.

09:19.810 --> 09:22.893
Exactly. You could be my lovely assistant.

09:22.980 --> 09:25.892
- If I wasn’t your boss.
- Right.

09:25.983 --> 09:28.725
Okay, her password. We are in.

09:28.819 --> 09:32.687
Now | just search for the most recently
updated documents.

09:32.781 --> 09:35.272
“Viral mutation”?

09:38.996 --> 09:43.615
Okay, these are random notes
from an interview with Dr. Tessa Burke.

09:43.709 --> 09:46.075
Seems like they were talking about
mutation possibilities...

09:46.170 --> 09:48.411
of SARS, Lassa and yellow fever,

09:48.505 --> 09:52.214
all deadly viruses that could kill a lot
of people very quickly.

09:52.301 --> 09:53.711
Yeah.

09:53.802 --> 09:57.260
According to her notes,
Mia Garrett had two meetings with you...

09:57.347 --> 09:59.258
at your lab over the past few weeks?

09:59.349 --> 10:02.512
Yes. And we’re scheduled
for another one next week. Why?

10:02.603 --> 10:04.844
Mia’s dead, Dr. Burke.

10:04.938 --> 10:07.224
| just saw her. What happened?

10:07.316 --> 10:10.149
Well, she contracted a fatal illness.
It was blood—borne.

10:10.235 --> 10:13.102
Someone hid that fact
by disposing of her remains.

10:13.197 --> 10:17.236
She was working on an expose on the dangers
of mutating pandemics.

10:17.326 --> 10:20.989
I’m an expert in the field.
That’s why she wanted to interview me.

10:21.079 --> 10:24.867
But she was just a blogger.
Did you find her suspicions credible?

10:24.958 --> 10:28.621
Absolutely.
Mia’s work could have been very important.

10:28.712 --> 10:31.419
She could have raised public awareness,
saved lives.

10:31.507 --> 10:34.999
— I can’t believe she’s gone.
- Your lab works with infectious
diseases, doesn’t it?

10:35.093 --> 10:38.085
Yes. My lab is a biosafety
level—two facility.

10:38.180 --> 10:40.466
But we work primarily
with Lyme disease and hep “C.”

10:40.557 --> 10:43.674
Mmm. So she could have contracted something
in your lab, couldn’t she?

10:43.769 --> 10:45.259
Mine?
Yeah.

10:45.354 --> 10:48.972
God, no. Given the quantities we work with
and our safety protocols,

10:49.066 --> 10:51.352
you could lick any Petri dish in my lab—

10:51.443 --> 10:53.149
worst you’d get is
a bad case of the sniffles.

10:53.237 --> 10:55.979
But there could be something unexpected.
It happens. Right?

10:56.073 --> 10:57.938
The reason I’m asking is because...

10:58.033 --> 11:01.651
you seem to be one of the last people
Mia saw before she died.

11:01.745 --> 11:03.827
What are you suggesting? l was helping Mia.

11:03.914 --> 11:06.155
l was on her side.

11:06.250 --> 11:08.787
Of course. I apologize.

11:08.877 --> 11:11.334
I understand how that might have
made you feel defensive.

11:11.421 --> 11:14.663
lfthere’s nothing else, please tell
the C.D.C. or the Jeffersonian...

11:14.758 --> 11:17.750
I’d be happy to offer my assistance
if they need any help.

11:17.845 --> 11:21.884
Yeah. We have our best people working on it,
but I’ll let them know.

11:28.689 --> 11:30.225
[ Device Beeps ]

11:30.315 --> 11:32.306
We treated the different cultures
with antibiotics.

11:32.401 --> 11:35.143
- No responses, so we
have to assume it’s viral.
— That’s something.

11:35.237 --> 11:38.695
That’s very little something. This woman died
and began decomposing within 24 hours.

11:38.782 --> 11:42.946
That’s too fast to treat other
cases unless we can isolate
and identify a specific virus.

11:43.036 --> 11:44.776
And the more people who are infected,

11:44.872 --> 11:47.784
the greater the chance
that it mutates and becomes airborne.

11:47.875 --> 11:49.365
Exactly.

11:49.459 --> 11:51.871
Your expertise is being wasted
on bones, Dr. Brennan.

11:51.962 --> 11:54.795
Without my expertise,
you wouldn’t know as much as you do.

11:54.882 --> 11:56.998
A bone marrow sample
is the surest way to see...

11:57.092 --> 11:59.549
how the immune system
was so severely compromised.

11:59.636 --> 12:03.629
A big enough drop
in eosinophils or neutrophils...

12:03.724 --> 12:07.433
would guarantee the infection
would grow unimpeded.

12:12.900 --> 12:14.982
[Arastoo ]
This sample should narrow down...

12:15.068 --> 12:16.933
what kind of virus we’re dealing with.

12:17.029 --> 12:19.270
We need to bag her
until we do further testing.

12:19.364 --> 12:20.649
Okay.

12:22.492 --> 12:24.619
Okay. On three.

12:25.662 --> 12:27.948
One, two, three.

12:28.040 --> 12:30.907
— Ah!
- What? Are you okay, Mr. Vaziri?

12:31.001 --> 12:32.912
Something stuck me.
Something on her humerus.

12:33.003 --> 12:35.119
Let me see.

12:36.882 --> 12:39.498
We need to flush this with saline
and sodium hypochlorite immediately.

12:39.635 --> 12:41.796
And then I’ll be okay?
Let’s just do it now.

12:43.513 --> 12:46.255
- What’s happening?
— He was cut on the remains.

12:46.350 --> 12:47.886
— Get some rilpivirine.
— But—

12:47.976 --> 12:49.056
Just go!

12:49.144 --> 12:52.728
[Alarm Bell Ringing]

12:54.900 --> 12:57.892
We need to get as much
blood out as possible to delay infection.

12:57.986 --> 13:01.194
But if this doesn’t work, we don’t even know
how the virus multiplies or takes hold.

13:01.281 --> 13:03.146
- All we can do at this point.
- Take off my finger.

13:03.241 --> 13:05.493
You know how the circulatory system works.
That wouldn’t help now.

13:05.619 --> 13:07.575
Rilpivirine.
Okay.

13:07.663 --> 13:10.905
If the virus is in your system, hopefully,
this will reduce the rate of its growth.

13:10.999 --> 13:14.366
For God’s sakes, what the hell good
is the C.D.C. if you let this happen?

13:14.461 --> 13:17.123
It’s not his fault. We followed all
the protocols. Something cut me.

13:17.214 --> 13:21.082
This is the cause. I found it
embedded in the desiccated
tissue on the victim’s humerus.

13:21.176 --> 13:23.963
- Which victim? There seem to be two now.
— Cam.

13:24.054 --> 13:25.669
— I’m sorry.
— What is it?

13:25.764 --> 13:27.345
It’s the tip of a micro needle.

13:27.432 --> 13:32.222
I found it when l was reexamining
the humerus on Mia’s M.R.l.

13:34.064 --> 13:37.648
That’s how she was infected. The gauge
is so small, she probably didn’t even feel it.

13:37.734 --> 13:39.986
While you culture that,
we’ll get Arastoo to the hospital.

13:40.070 --> 13:41.526
Why? To get a tetanus shot?

13:41.613 --> 13:43.649
We don’t even know what’s in me
or how to treat it.

13:43.740 --> 13:45.480
And his immune system
would be compromised.

13:45.575 --> 13:48.032
He could get a lethal secondary infection
at the hospital.

13:48.120 --> 13:49.781
And I could potentially infect other people.

13:49.871 --> 13:52.283
So we just let you die like Mia Garrett?

13:52.374 --> 13:54.740
No. You use me.

13:54.835 --> 13:58.202
The Jeffersonian has all the equipment
we’d find at a hospital.

13:58.296 --> 14:00.457
lfl get sick, you can study my symptoms.

14:00.549 --> 14:02.881
It’s the best way to discover what illness
we’re dealing with.

14:02.968 --> 14:05.835
- He’s right, Cam.
- This is now bigger
than one man, Dr. Saroyan.

14:05.929 --> 14:09.046
— Not to me.
— You don’t mean that, Cam.

14:09.141 --> 14:11.052
I could be the key.

14:13.729 --> 14:15.936
You know this is what has to be done.

14:17.274 --> 14:19.936
Is there a room where he can
be isolated and observed?

14:26.033 --> 14:28.991
Guys, I need the bone room
cleared and secured.

14:29.077 --> 14:30.863
Get a hospital bed, cardiac monitors,

14:30.954 --> 14:33.491
a ventilator, defibrillator,
nasogastric tubes...

14:33.582 --> 14:35.823
and equipment for peritoneal dialysis.

14:35.917 --> 14:37.578
Got it.

14:40.297 --> 14:42.208
- [ Boot/7 [Arastoo is sick?
— Potentially.

14:42.299 --> 14:43.709
He’s not exhibiting any symptoms.

14:43.800 --> 14:45.461
We/i, yet. How about you?

14:45.552 --> 14:47.713
— I’m fine. Everyone else is fine.
— I’m coming over.

14:47.804 --> 14:51.217
No, Booth. The protocols
have been lightened. They won ’i let you in.

14:51.308 --> 14:53.094
— l’l/be fine.
— You sure?

14:53.185 --> 14:56.222
Yes. Just focus on your end of the case.

14:56.313 --> 14:59.476
That’s how you can help.
But wait. Take a look at this.

14:59.566 --> 15:03.559
You gotta be kidding me. Someone tried
to kill her by injecting the virus?

15:03.653 --> 15:07.521
The injection site on Mia Garrett appears
to be on her posterior humerus.

15:07.616 --> 15:09.607
Then they covered it up
so no one would find out.

15:09.701 --> 15:13.535
Yes. Once the virus is identified,
it could lead directly to the killer.

15:13.622 --> 15:15.658
Which means that you haven’t
identified it yet.

15:16.666 --> 15:19.043
We’re still waiting for test results.

15:19.127 --> 15:21.914
— What happened with Burke
and the boyfriend?
— I got nothing.

